\title{Karpathy Guidelines}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Behavioral guidelines to reduce common LLM coding mistakes. Use when writing, reviewing, or refactoring code to avoid overcomplication, make surgical changes, surface assumptions, and define verifiable success criteria.}

\subtree{
\title{Karpathy Guidelines}
\p{Behavioral guidelines to reduce common LLM coding mistakes, derived from [Andrej Karpathy's observations](https://x.com/karpathy/status/2015883857489522876) on LLM coding pitfalls.}

\p{\strong{Tradeoff:} These guidelines bias toward caution over speed. For trivial tasks, use judgment.}

\subtree{
\title{1. Think Before Coding}
\p{\strong{Don't assume. Don't hide confusion. Surface tradeoffs.}}

\p{Before implementing:}

\ul{
\li{State your assumptions explicitly. If uncertain, ask.}
\li{If multiple interpretations exist, present them - don't pick silently.}
\li{If a simpler approach exists, say so. Push back when warranted.}
\li{If something is unclear, stop. Name what's confusing. Ask.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{2. Simplicity First}
\p{\strong{Minimum code that solves the problem. Nothing speculative.}}

\ul{
\li{No features beyond what was asked.}
\li{No abstractions for single-use code.}
\li{No "flexibility" or "configurability" that wasn't requested.}
\li{No error handling for impossible scenarios.}
\li{If you write 200 lines and it could be 50, rewrite it.}
}

\p{Ask yourself: "Would a senior engineer say this is overcomplicated?" If yes, simplify.}
}

\subtree{
\title{3. Surgical Changes}
\p{\strong{Touch only what you must. Clean up only your own mess.}}

\p{When editing existing code:}

\ul{
\li{Don't "improve" adjacent code, comments, or formatting.}
\li{Don't refactor things that aren't broken.}
\li{Match existing style, even if you'd do it differently.}
\li{If you notice unrelated dead code, mention it - don't delete it.}
}

\p{When your changes create orphans:}

\ul{
\li{Remove imports/variables/functions that YOUR changes made unused.}
\li{Don't remove pre-existing dead code unless asked.}
}

\p{The test: Every changed line should trace directly to the user's request.}
}

\subtree{
\title{4. Goal-Driven Execution}
\p{\strong{Define success criteria. Loop until verified.}}

\p{Transform tasks into verifiable goals:}

\ul{
\li{"Add validation" → "Write tests for invalid inputs, then make them pass"}
\li{"Fix the bug" → "Write a test that reproduces it, then make it pass"}
\li{"Refactor X" → "Ensure tests pass before and after"}
}

\p{For multi-step tasks, state a brief plan:}

\pre{\startverb
1. [Step] → verify: [check]
2. [Step] → verify: [check]
3. [Step] → verify: [check]
\stopverb}

\p{Strong success criteria let you loop independently. Weak criteria ("make it work") require constant clarification.}
}
}